<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1437,225,828]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,261,288]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Carapace pyriform, covered with thin layer of setae. Pseudorostral spines cylindrical, straight, long, diverging in V. Supraorbital eave fused with carapace, slight pre-orbital angle. Postorbital lobe elongated, rounded distal margin. Carapace regions defined with long spines. Basal antennal article longer than broad, narrow in width. Pterygostomal region with granules. Chelipeds slender. Ambulatory legs slender; P2 longest. Adult female pleon rounded, with all somites and telson free.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1437,225,828]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,442,468]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Etymology.</emphasis>
The Latin name for the new genus is derived from the characteristic lack of pre-orbital lobe that is analogous to the lack of an “eyebrow” for the 
<typeStatus box="[673,721,478,504]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">type</typeStatus>
species, where “ 
<emphasis box="[913,944,479,504]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Ne</emphasis>
” means “not” in both Greek and Latin, and “ 
<emphasis box="[164,240,514,540]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">ophrys</emphasis>
” means “eyebrow” in Greek. Gender feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="34" pageNumber="35" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1437,225,828]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,550,576]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Lee &amp; Forges &amp; Ng, 2019" authorityName="Lee &amp; Forges &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2019" box="[323,546,550,576]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Neophrys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inopinata" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[323,546,550,576]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Neophrys inopinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[555,619,550,576]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[555,619,550,576]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
in this genus is completely covered with a layer of short velvet-like tomentum, as in the two other genera, 
<taxonomicName authority="Ng, Komai &amp; Sato, 2017" authorityName="Ng, Komai &amp; Sato" authorityYear="2017" box="[568,1010,586,612]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Tunepugettia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[568,714,587,612]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Tunepugettia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Ng, P. K. L. &amp; Komai, T. &amp; Sato, T." box="[722,1010,586,612]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="133 - 152" refId="ref28986" refString="Ng, P. K. L., Komai, T. &amp; Sato, T. (2017) On the trail of a Japanese &quot; ghost species &quot; the identify of Goniopugettia tanakae Sakai, 1986, and the establishment of a new genus for Pugettia sagamiensis Gordon, 1930 (Decapoda, Brahyura, Epialtidae). Crustacean Research, 46, 133 - 152." type="journal article" year="2017">Ng, Komai &amp; Sato, 2017</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Lee &amp; Forges &amp; Ng, 2019" authorityName="Lee &amp; Forges &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2019" box="[1071,1226,586,612]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Crocydocinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[1071,1226,586,612]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Crocydocinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1234,1314,586,612]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1234,1314,586,612]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">n. gen.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
There are, however, many differences. The prominent pre-orbital angle seen in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lee &amp; Forges &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2019" box="[916,1017,622,648]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[916,1017,622,648]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Rochinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and allied genera is absent in 
<taxonomicName authority="Lee &amp; Forges &amp; Ng, 2019" authorityName="Lee &amp; Forges &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2019" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Neophrys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Neophrys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[192,270,658,684]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,270,658,684]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">n. gen.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
The species in 
<taxonomicName authority="Lee &amp; Forges &amp; Ng, 2019" authorityName="Lee &amp; Forges &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2019" box="[442,549,658,684]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Neophrys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[442,549,658,684]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Neophrys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[556,634,658,684]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[556,634,658,684]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">n. gen.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
has similar long lateral branchial spines as the species in 
<taxonomicName authority="Ng &amp; Richer de Forges, 2013" authorityName="Ng &amp; Richer de Forges" authorityYear="2013" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Samadinia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1276,1396,658,684]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Samadinia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Richer de Forges, B. &amp; Ng, P. K. L." pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="467 - 483" refId="ref30088" refString="Richer de Forges, B. &amp; Ng, P. K. L. (2013) On a collection of spider crabs of the genera Rochinia A. Milne-Edwards, 1875 and Naxioides A. Milne-Edwards, 1865 (Crustacea, Brachyura, Majoidea, Epialtidae) from Mozambique Channel, Solomon, Vanuatu and Philippine Islands, with description of a new species of Rochinia. In: Ahyong, S. T., Chan, T. Y., Corbari, L. &amp; Ng, P. K. L. (Eds.), Tropical Deep-sea Benthos 27. Museum national d'Histoire naturelle, Paris, pp. 467 - 483." type="book chapter" year="2013">Ng &amp; Richer de Forges, 2013</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but the species in this genus have long hepatic spines that is directed outwards, which is typically a short spine in other genera. As there are no male specimens known for this genus, the pleonal characters of this genus were not compared between the other morphological close genera. 
<taxonomicName authority="Lee &amp; Forges &amp; Ng, 2019" authorityName="Lee &amp; Forges &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2019" box="[1107,1214,766,792]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Neophrys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[1107,1214,766,792]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Neophrys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1222,1301,766,792]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1222,1301,766,792]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">n. gen.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is currently monotypic, with only one species known thus far.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
